thread.title: Duluth homicide victim was UMD student, son of St. Paul officer
thread.title_full: Duluth homicide victim was UMD student, son of St. Paul officer - StarTribune.com

author: Karen Zamora
title: Duluth homicide victim was UMD student, son of St. Paul officer

organizations.name: swenson college of science and engineering

text:
The 22-year-old man who was fatally shot Tuesday afternoon in Duluth was a college student from Centerville, authorities said Wednesday.
William Andrew Grahek, a student at the University of Minnesota Duluth, was shot on the 500 block of E. 11th Street. He was taken to a hospital where he died, Duluth police said in a statement.
Grahek grew up in Centerville and graduated from Centennial High School. He was a junior enrolled in both the Swenson College of Science and Engineering and the College of Liberal Arts at UMD, according to the Associated Press.
He also served as a specialist with the 312th Army Reserve Engineer Company located on Park Point.
Grahek is the son of St. Paul police Sgt. Jon Grahek, according to a statement from St. Paul police.
“The Graheks do not wish to make a public statement other than to say that they loved William very much and to thank everyone who has reached out to them with comforting words and support,” according to the statement from St. Paul police.
UMD Vice Chancellor for Student Life Lisa Erwin said in a prepared statement that the campus community is mourning for Grahek and extends condolences to his family and friends, according to the Associated Press.
About 2 p.m. Tuesday, officers responded to E. 11th Street on a report of a shooting, according to a news release. The shooting had taken place inside a residence.
A “person of interest” was detained Tuesday night, but on Wednesday police said they have no one in custody.
Officers have identified a possible motive but have yet to release further information. Agents from the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives are assisting in the investigation.
